{
  "answer": "**In \"The Seafarer\" (chapter 5 of *Old English Elegies*), the speaker describes how the cuckoo's mournful cry—along with spring's beauties like blooming groves and bright meadows—urges the soul of the eager wanderer to depart on a sea journey.**[^1]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/#p-f52e2e).  \n*\"The groves bear their blossoms, the boroughs grow fair, / the meadows are bright, the world rushes onward; / and all this urges the eager of heart, / the soul to set out on its journey... / The cuckoo calls too, with its mournful cry, / summer's warden sings, sowing a sorrow / bitter in the breast-hoard.\"*",
